, England, United Kingdom":"Nazeing, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Stapleford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stapleford, Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","White Notley, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"White Notley, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","White Notley, Essex, England":"White Notley, Essex, England","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Essex, England":"Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1267–1307":"1267–1307","1273–1307":"1273–1307","1306–Female":"1306–Deceased","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1345–1399":"1345–1399","1243–1270":"1243–1270","1245–1285":"1245–1285","1285":"1285","1273":"1273","1293":"1293","1270":"1270","1345":"1345","1267":"1267","1245":"1245","1399":"1399","1300":"1300","1243":"1243","about 1300":"about 1300","1307":"1307","Aft 1270":"after 1270","1306":"1306","Nazeing, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Nazeing, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Stapleford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Stapleford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","White Notley, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"White Notley, Essex, England, United Kingdom","White Notley, Essex, England":"White Notley, Essex, England","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wright","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name for a craftsman or maker of machinery, mostly in wood, of any of a wide range of kinds, from Middle English and Older Scots <i>wriht</i>, <i>wright</i>, <i>wricht</i>, <i>writh</i>, <i>write</i> (Old English <i>wyrhta</i>, <i>wryhta</i>) ‘craftsman’, especially ‘carpenter, joiner’. The term is found in various combinations (for example,   Cartwright   and   Wainwright  ), but when used in isolation it often referred to a builder of windmills or watermills. This surname is also very common among African Americans."],"variants":[{"name":"Wrights","meanings":["(1997: 103;2007: 204; 2010: NA)","English: variant of   Wright  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Wrightsman","meanings":["Probably English (although no longer found in Britain), meaning‘servant of the wright’ (see   Wright  )."]},{"name":"Cartwright","meanings":["English (Midlands and northern England): occupational name from Middle English <i>cart(e)</i> ‘cart’ + <i>wright(e)</i> ‘craftsman’ (Old English <i>cræt</i> or Old Norse <i>kartr</i> + Old English <i>wyrhta</i>), for a cartwright, a maker of carts.","Variant of   Courtright  , a surname of Dutch origin."]},{"name":"Wrightson","meanings":["English (northern England, especially Durham): patronymic from   Wright  , meaning ‘son of the wright’."]},{"name":"Right","meanings":["(2007: 493; 2010: NA)","English: variant of   Wright  ."]},{"name":"McWright","meanings":["Scottish or Irish: Gaelic patronymic with the English and Scots occupational term   Wright  , meaning ‘son of the wright’. The name is possibly a part translation of   McIntyre  , which fully translates as ‘son of the wright’."]},{"name":"Wrightman","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>wright</i> ‘craftsman’ (see   Wright  ) + <i>man</i> ‘man’, denoting someone who assisted a craftsman."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Wright I was born in 1267, in Stapleford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert William Wright, was 24 and his mother, Dorothy de Montfort, was 22. He married Dorothy Whitbread in 1293, in White Notley, Essex, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1307, in Whit